h3. Issue Summary

Customers are facing issues while using Jira colorpicker URI in one of the plugins(Zephyr). It is Jira URI throwing 404 error (OOP's you have found a dead link) when they try to access this page.
{code:java}
http://JIRA_URL/secure/popups/colorpicker.jsp?element=statusColor
{code}
The problem is reproducible on Jira 8.12.0 and 8.12.1 versions.

The problem is because of missing files:
{code:java}
colorpicker_jsp.class --> from the directory $JIRA_INSTALL/atlassian-jira/WEB-INF/classes/jsp/secure/popups/colorpicker_jsp.class
{code}
{code:java}
colorpicker_jsp.class --> from the directory $JIRA_INSTALL/atlassian-jira/WEB-INF/classes/jsp/template/standard/colorpicker_jsp.class
{code}
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Install Jira Software 8.12.0 version and login to Jira instance.
 # Try to access the URLs mentioned below by editing the URL in a different tab.
{code:java}
http://JIRA_URL/secure/popups/colorpicker.jsp
{code}
{code:java}
http://JIRA_URL/secure/popups/colorpicker.jsp?element=statusColor
{code}

h3. Expected Results

It should return a popup a window for color selection (screenshot attached).
h3. Actual Results

We get 404 error page Oops, you've found a dead link (screenshot attached).
h3. Workaround

Currently there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available.

Problem:
The *Move the JavaMail Classes* section of [Configuring an SMTP mail server to send notifications|https://confluence.atlassian.com/adminjiraserver/configuring-an-smtp-mail-server-to-send-notifications-947184044.html] mentions:

{quote}If the application server already contains mail-1.4.1.jar and activation-1.1.1.jar, then just remove mail-1.4.1.jar and activation-1.1.1.jar from{quote}

However in recent Jira versions, the names of these jars are:
{code}
javax.mail-1.6.2.jar
jakarta.mail-1.6.5.jar
jakarta.activation-1.1.1.jar
{code}
We have to make clearer that these are the jar that needed to be moved

With an external user directory(ies), the *“rest/api/2/group/member”* endpoint is extremely slow to respond (~2.5+ minutes), even when limiting the response size to the first 50 users.

If the current approach can’t be sped up, as an admin, I’d like the ability to check group membership against cached/potentially stale results (with an extra query param flag or something similar).

The current behavior goes directly to the database and examines the contents of all user directories, with a lot of churn to handle duplicate user names across directories.
 * *Environment:-* Jira + Embedded crowd

 h5. Replication:
- Have more than 1000 users in External directory (ies)
- Call both the API's (_as the error observed in both the API's are same_)

{code:java}
 https://base-url/rest/api/2/group/member?groupname=jira-users&startAt=0&maxResults=49 
{code}

{code:java}
https://base-url/rest/api/2/group?groupname=jira-users&expand=users&startAt=0&maxresult=49 
{code}
